CommonFields.Title: Toward the development of a quantitative tool for predicting dispersion of nanocomposites under non-equilibrium processing conditions
Author: Hassinger, Irene
Li, Xiaolin
Zhao, He
Xu, Hongyi
Huang, Yanhui
Prasad, Aditya
Schadler, Linda
Chen, Wei
Brinson, L. Catherine

Matrix.Description: The powder size of the PMMA was 200–650 um and Tg is around 98 deg C.

Mixing.Description: 50 ml tetrahydrofuran (THF) and 16ml of the silica nanoparticles in solvent were refluxed at 70 deg C for 24 h under nitrogen atmosphere.

Heating.Description: The mixture was cooled down to room temperature

Drying-Evaporation.Description: The THF was reduced to 20 ml in a rotor evaporator in order to reduce the amount of needed hexane.

Mixing.Description: The mixture was precipitated in 200 ml of hexane. The particles were then centrifuged at 10,000 rpm for 10 min at 10 deg C
the particles modified with APDEMS were redispersed in THF.

Drying-Evaporation.Description: After evaporation of the water or ethanol, the nanoparticle-polymer mixture was dried in a vacuum oven for 12 h.

Mixing.Description: The mixtures were then milled in a jet milling machine in order to reduce the starting agglomerate size.

Transmission_Electron_Microscopy.Description: To observe the dispersion of the nanoparticles in the polymer matrix, the materials were embedded in an epoxy matrix and slices of *50 nm were sectioned at room temperature in an ultramicrotome using a diamond knife. The sections were collected on a copper grid and imaged in a JEOL-2010 transmission electron microscope (TEM).

Thermogravimetric_Analysis.Description: The particle content of the nanocomposites was determined with thermo-gravimetric analysis (TGA). The samples were first heated at 10 K/min up to 700 C and then the temperature was kept at 700 C for 5 min.

Rheometery.Description: The viscosity of the samples was measured in a parallelplate rheometer. The samples were pressed at 180 C. The sample size was 25 mm and the gap was set to 2 mm. The shear rate was changed in the rotation mode at a temperature of 180 C for PP; 200, 210, 220 C for PS; and 220, 230 C for PMMA. For samples with high viscosity that could not be measured at 180 C, the samples were measured at higher temperature and the viscosity at 180 C was calculated according to the Arrhenius Eq. 1 [16, 37].
